WEBVTT

00:00:03.640 --> 00:00:08.500
Okay, so hi everybody, welcome to our talk on transparent

00:00:08.660 --> 00:00:09.100
feeds.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:11.680
I'm Udet, and this is Cole.

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:15.240
We're from Haifa Worker Co-op and Star

00:00:15.320 --> 00:00:16.430
ling Lab.

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:19.160
Haifa is a tech worker co-op.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:22.920
We do a bunch of things, and Starling Lab is

00:00:22.920 --> 00:00:29.700
a lab that focuses on questions around information integrity, based out

00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:31.940
of Stanford and USC.

00:00:31.980 --> 00:00:36.060
I probably don't have to convince a lot of you that

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:40.420
misinformation and disinformation are growing concerns.

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:43.900
For example, some of you may have seen the image on

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:46.000
the right on social media.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.280
This is an image claiming to be about the war in the

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:50.360
Middle East.

00:00:50.380 --> 00:00:51.820
It's actually false.

00:00:51.820 --> 00:00:53.980
The real image is the one on the left, which is

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:57.370
the satellite image from a few years ago.

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:00.900
When we have both of these images shown together, with the

00:01:00.990 --> 00:01:03.800
context you know that the one on the right is false,

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:06.140
but often we don't have all the context, and it

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:11.080
's hard to tell what images are real and what images are

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:11.900
fake.

00:01:11.900 --> 00:01:15.790
We think this is a growing concern, not only because f

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:20.260
akes promote false narratives, but also fakes make it easier

00:01:20.260 --> 00:01:22.910
for bad actors to deny reality.

00:01:22.920 --> 00:01:25.520
This is called the Liar's Dividend, and

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:28.120
we think one of the things that's going to happen with

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:32.270
this is increasingly we're going to see an erosion of accountability

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:36.780
and sort of assault on democracy.

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:40.150
So what can we do, and specifically what can we do

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:44.980
in the blue sky and atmosphere context?

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:49.150
And so one of the things we've been working on is

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:53.420
the Nectar API, which is a similar image search

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:53.920
API.

00:01:53.920 --> 00:01:58.280
So you can find similar images on the atmosphere.

00:01:58.280 --> 00:02:00.610
One of the things we do is we run a bunch of

00:02:00.610 --> 00:02:05.500
image fingerprinting in the background, so we fingerprint all images

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:08.020
coming through the Firehose.

00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:11.120
And on top of that, to demo exactly how you can

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:15.920
use this in a misinformation and disinformation context, we've

00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:21.010
built a browser extension called Pollen, which makes it easier

00:02:21.010 --> 00:02:27.150
for us to attach provenance claims and add context to images

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:27.600
.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:29.930
And I'm going to hand it over to Cole to demo

00:02:29.930 --> 00:02:32.020
what this looks like in practice.

00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:34.740
All right.

00:02:34.740 --> 00:02:38.420
So here's just a quick video demo of Pollen.

00:02:38.420 --> 00:02:39.390
Here we're on bsky.

00:02:39.390 --> 00:02:41.680
app, the regular website, and we have our Pollen

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:44.360
browser extension loaded into the browser.

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:46.920
And we're looking at an example news account that we created

00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:48.780
for the demo called News123.

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:52.780
And in this demo, they post headlines, stories, they

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:54.400
post photographs.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:58.470
So we're about to see them make a post, which

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:00.980
we'll see in one moment.

00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:03.800
And the post is about the Chicago River being dyed green for

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:04.080
St.

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:07.330
Patrick's Day, which just happened this past March 17th

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:07.560
.

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:09.510
And they're going to attach an image from one of their

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:11.140
photojournalists of that happening.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.570
So far, this is just a regular blue sky flow and

00:03:13.570 --> 00:03:16.130
nothing has been modified by our extension.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:17.140
There's the image.

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:20.310
They're going to post it and it goes into their PD

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:20.660
S.

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:22.810
But when they post that image, if they hover over it

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:25.700
, they're going to see in the corner this claim button

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:25.980
.

00:03:25.980 --> 00:03:28.380
And the claim button is a button being added by our browser

00:03:28.380 --> 00:03:31.040
extension, where any user can make a claim on any other

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:32.420
image on the network.

00:03:32.420 --> 00:03:35.240
And they get this text box where they can enter more information

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:36.780
, more context on the image.

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:38.680
We call this like a claim.

00:03:38.680 --> 00:03:40.890
And so in this case, News123 is going to

00:03:40.890 --> 00:03:42.520
add a claim on their own image.

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:44.680
They're going to say something about their own content.

00:03:44.680 --> 00:03:46.680
It could be any user's content.

00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:48.320
But in this case, it's their own.

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:50.830
And so they're going to put just a little piece of

00:03:50.830 --> 00:03:51.820
text in there.

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:53.980
They're going to describe the content of the image, say

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:56.180
, you know, this is the Chicago River.

00:03:56.200 --> 00:03:57.680
We took the photo on this day.

00:03:57.680 --> 00:03:58.680
It was taken by us, News123.

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:01.990
And so they're just adding that context to the image itself

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:02.260
.

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:04.750
And they click Create, and immediately we see, thanks to

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:06.100
the extension, one claim.

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:08.560
And we see this drawer here that's been created by the

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:12.180
extension, where you can see the account that created it.

00:04:12.180 --> 00:04:16.060
And you can see the text of their claim.

00:04:16.060 --> 00:04:18.020
If you open the claim and look at it, you see

00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:19.320
it's not a blue sky post.

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:21.030
It's our own kind of claim record, and it has

00:04:21.030 --> 00:04:23.210
extra data in there, and it has a perceptual hash

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:23.650
.

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:24.960
It has the text.

00:04:24.960 --> 00:04:26.320
It has a link to the original post.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:29.580
So we have all this important information that's attached.

00:04:29.580 --> 00:04:32.330
But when this really comes into play is when you see it

00:04:32.330 --> 00:04:33.760
in other contexts.

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:35.860
So we're going to switch to a different account for the

00:04:35.860 --> 00:04:37.460
demo called Mallory.

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:40.120
Mallory gets her information from all kinds of other sources,

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:42.740
maybe Facebook and Instagram, as well as blue sky.

00:04:42.740 --> 00:04:45.560
Maybe she wants to misinform people maliciously.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.580
Maybe she's just misinformed herself, but in any case

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:50.420
, she's writing her own post.

00:04:50.420 --> 00:04:52.780
She's writing, "Toxic spill turns a river

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:55.520
neon green in London." Totally different idea.

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:56.900
And she's attaching her own image.

00:04:56.900 --> 00:04:59.330
This is a different image that she's going to attach,

00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:00.900
coming from a different site.

00:05:00.900 --> 00:05:02.320
It's got a smaller resolution.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:04.270
It's more compressed, which you can see a little bit

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:05.540
on the left side there.

00:05:05.540 --> 00:05:08.740
The visual content is obviously the same, but the image bites

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:09.360
the CID.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:11.380
It's totally different.

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:14.530
And so she's going to post that to her PDS

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:14.880
.

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:17.440
And what we see immediately, one claim.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:19.620
So that's the Nectar API and the pollen browser

00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:24.330
extension, carrying through this claim information because it's matched these

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:26.140
visually similar images.

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:28.680
And so we see a different idea that it's the Chicago

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:30.100
River that's been died.

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:31.240
This contradicts Mallory.

00:05:31.240 --> 00:05:33.390
And as a viewer, as a user, we get to

00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:36.640
decide who we trust, News123 or Mallory.

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:38.020
We also get some extra information.

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:40.540
We get to see the user name and we get to see

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:41.720
95% match.

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.720
It's our matching algorithm at work just telling you how close

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.260
these images are visually.

00:05:46.280 --> 00:05:49.480
95% is pretty high, and so that's great.

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:52.320
We also see view claimed post, which is a button that

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:54.820
takes you to the original post the claim is on.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:56.760
So you can trace the provenance of the image.

00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.050
So you can find the original place that the claim was made

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:01.860
and allow you to see, like, you know, if

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:03.900
you don't trust the matching algorithm, you can see what

00:06:03.980 --> 00:06:06.430
the actual original image was and all that kind of stuff.

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:09.280
So that's just a simple demo of extension.

00:06:09.280 --> 00:06:11.950
We think the really interesting thing here is that we've now

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:15.880
created the ability to create records that refer to images themselves,

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:18.680
not just records that refer to posts, like when you make

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.280
a reply on the network.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:23.600
So if we move to the next slide, so yeah,

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:26.080
in Pollen we've just created text claims.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:28.510
We think there's lots to explore here with different kinds of

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:29.040
claims.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:31.280
You could do a geolocation claim, for example.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:33.230
So users, instead of writing text, they put a pin

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:35.050
on a map and they're claiming, you know, this

00:06:35.050 --> 00:06:36.600
photo was taken in this location.

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.360
You could do timestamping claims.

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:40.080
Every record already has a timestamp.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.650
But if you want to prove when an image was taken,

00:06:42.650 --> 00:06:45.000
you can use external parties to do that.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:47.540
You can register the image on a blockchain like the Cardano

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:50.400
blockchain, put that registration in the record, and that proves

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:53.020
the image existed before at a certain point in time.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:55.730
Or you can use a third party with a trusted timestamp

00:06:55.730 --> 00:06:58.170
ing protocol that signs the hash of the image.

00:06:58.180 --> 00:06:59.440
You insert that signature.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:01.660
Anyway, there's lots of different things you can do.

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:04.010
We think this is like an open standard that we've created

00:07:04.010 --> 00:07:05.240
that people can explore.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:06.340
You could do like voice notes.

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:08.870
You could do all kinds of different cool claims with Pollen

00:07:08.870 --> 00:07:09.080
.

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:11.240
So just to recap, we've created Nectar,

00:07:11.240 --> 00:07:14.600
which is an API to find similar images across the atmosphere with

00:07:14.650 --> 00:07:16.960
perceptual hashing, which I'm happy to talk about

00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:17.520
afterward.

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:20.720
And then we created Pollen as an example demo.

00:07:20.980 --> 00:07:23.370
But we think there's lots of cool other use cases that

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:24.660
you can do with this API.

00:07:24.660 --> 00:07:27.480
You could track image reposts across the network.

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:29.980
You could use it for trust and safety to do moderation of

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:30.920
similar images.

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:34.900
You could do social research like the previous talk where you track

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:38.220
like, okay, this image has been posted this many times

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:39.800
over this time frame.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:41.380
You could do community notes.

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:44.390
We see Pollen as like step towards the idea of community

00:07:44.390 --> 00:07:46.990
notes on Blue Sky and on the atmosphere at large.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:50.360
And you could also do rights management to track copyrighted content

00:07:50.470 --> 00:07:52.780
or just content you didn't want to be posted.

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:53.820
Excuse me.

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:56.220
So that's Nectar.

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:58.030
You can check us out at nectar.

00:07:58.030 --> 00:07:58.560
hypha.

00:07:58.560 --> 00:07:59.120
coop.

00:07:59.120 --> 00:08:02.230
If you're interested in adding image annotations to your application

00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:05.180
or image search to your application, if you want to collaborate

00:08:05.180 --> 00:08:08.310
with us on this project, fund the project, partner with

00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:10.900
us, either reach out in person to Udit or myself

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:12.770
, or check us out at nectar.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:13.580
hypha.

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:14.160
coop.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:15.360
So thank you very much.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:23.230
If we have time for questions.

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:27.180
Thank you.

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:30.180
I see the screenplay poster right here.

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:34.320
I know Eli recently published a blog about using scuba and

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:38.950
muzzle, some standards to try to ensure hashing of

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:43.740
videos for authenticity along relatively similar lines.

00:08:43.740 --> 00:08:47.450
I'm curious if you look into those standards, do you

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:51.230
think the UX for images and video can be similar in this

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:51.860
way?

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:56.680
Yeah, so just to repeat the question, it's about

00:08:56.860 --> 00:09:02.980
whether Eli's standards around video hashing are relevant to our

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:03.900
work.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:06.460
So yeah, we've actually worked with Eli, and we

00:09:06.460 --> 00:09:08.820
discussed the standard and everything.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:12.440
The actual technical details of how this works, we're using

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:15.310
perceptual hashing, so it's slightly different than the

00:09:15.310 --> 00:09:17.220
idea of cryptographic hashes that match.

00:09:17.220 --> 00:09:19.960
We also did create a standard for perceptual hashing with

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:21.750
Dazzle, which is with Dazzle, Robin

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:23.640
, who's working at Dazzle there.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:27.860
But it's still relevant, right?

00:09:27.860 --> 00:09:31.420
Maybe less so with exact hash matching, but there are has

00:09:31.470 --> 00:09:34.930
hes that apply to video that could be used to match similar

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:36.200
video content.

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:40.200
We started with images because that's like the easiest lift,

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:43.000
but you could expand it to video, audio, and so

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:43.820
on, text.

00:09:43.820 --> 00:09:45.940
So it's definitely applicable.

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:49.480
Okay, thank you very much.

00:09:49.480 --> 00:09:50.480
Thank you.
